When slow path ELT is enabled on linux, this will allocate 128 bytes of stack buffer for each function that the profiler can use to copy any enregistered structs to. I chose 128 because that is the size of the available general purpose registers + the available floating point registers for argument passing (since we store the xmm values in the profiler code as 64 bit). Previously we were allocatng 216 bytes of stack space to store the registers, so while this grows the stack usage by ~50% I believe this is an acceptable tradeoff for slow path ELT.

`ProfileArgIterator::CopyStructFromRegisters` is `ArgLocDesc::CopyStructToRegisters` but modified to work with `PROFILE_PLATFORM_SPECIFIC_DATA` instead of `TransitionBlock`, and also to copy out of registers instead of in to registers. `PROFILE_PLATFORM_SPECIFIC_DATA` has a different layout, and uses `UINT64` for all float registers, including the 128 bit registers.

